<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="280" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,766,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">Discussion.</emphasis>
The similarity between 
<taxonomicName box="[608,727,767,791]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pazukii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[608,727,767,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. pazukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[735,825,766,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[735,825,766,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[882,1037,768,791]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritarsis">
<emphasis box="[882,1037,768,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. nigritarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based on the shape of the lateral margins of the hypandrium in ventral view (compare 
<figureCitation box="[774,843,802,827]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 7" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1764,1787]" captionTargetBox="[220,1402,210,1722]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1743]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 7. Myolepta pazukii Gilasian &amp; Reemer sp. nov. (male holotype). 5. Abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.5 mm; 6. Hypandrium, lateral view; 7. Hypandrium, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/255698/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">
Fig. 
<number box="[829,843,803,826]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
with Fig. 
<number box="[967,995,803,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="12.0">12</number>
e in 
<bibRefCitation author="Reemer" box="[1049,1277,803,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" refString="Reemer, M., Hauser, M. &amp; Speight, M. C. D. (2004) The genus Myolepta Newman in the West-Palaearctic region (Diptera, Syrphidae). Studia dipterologica, 11 (2), 553 - 580." type="journal article" year="2004">
Reemer 
<emphasis box="[1147,1206,803,827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1216,1277,803,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<number box="[1290,1334,802,827]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="576.0">576</number>
) and the pilosity of mesonotum. The most obvious differences between these two species are found in the colouration of the abdomen and leg, which spark the impression that these taxa are colour varieties of the same species, possibly originating from climatic differences between 
<collectingCountry box="[677,722,912,935]" name="Iran" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">Iran</collectingCountry>
(whence 
<taxonomicName box="[833,952,911,935]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pazukii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[833,952,911,935]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. pazukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[960,1052,910,935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[960,1052,910,935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is described) and western Europe and 
<collectingCountry box="[198,278,946,971]" name="Turkey" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">Turkey</collectingCountry>
(from where 
<taxonomicName box="[429,584,947,970]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritarsis">
<emphasis box="[429,584,947,970]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. nigritarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known). However, the additional morphological characters listed in 
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,239,1588,1611]" captionTargetBox="[159,1415,1639,1990]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="TABLE 1. Morphological differences between males of M. pazukii sp. nov. and M. nigritarsis." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/09F6666F1036D216769BDC63B3886E03" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" tableUuid="09F6666F1036D216769BDC63B3886E03">
Table 
<number box="[151,165,983,1007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
do not support this idea. Besides, if 
<taxonomicName box="[594,715,983,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pazukii" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[594,715,983,1007]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. pazukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[724,816,982,1007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[724,816,982,1007]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
would be a pale colour variety of 
<taxonomicName box="[1220,1377,984,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritarsis">
<emphasis box="[1220,1377,984,1007]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. nigritarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with partly yellow legs and yellow posterior margins of tergites 
<number box="[815,860,1019,1043]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
, then it would be quite unexpected that at the same time the yellow spots on tergite 
<number box="[521,535,1055,1079]" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" value="3.0">3</number>
are much smaller than in 
<taxonomicName box="[837,993,1056,1079]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigritarsis">
<emphasis box="[837,993,1056,1079]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. nigritarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For these reasons, we believe that 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Myolepta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pazukii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="280">M. pazukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a distinct species.
</paragraph>
